synopsis:
One individual with a de novo synonymous variant in TTN was documented in a large autism spectrum disorder cohort. 
plus 12 de novo variants in DDD study without clinical information

Forty individuals with TLK2-variants, including two affected mothers were published by Reijnders et al published (AJHG 2018). The clinical phenotype included language and motor delay (mostly mild-borderline), behavioral disorders (e.g. tantrums, autism spectrum disorder, ADHD) , neonatal feeding difficulties , gastro-intestinal problems (e.g. constipation), facial dysmorphism (including blepharophimosis), short stature (37%), microcephaly (24%), brain abnormality (25%), eye anomalies (refraction abnormality, strabimus) and variable other anomalies. Since then a few case reports have been published.

One individual with a de novo missense variant in RBMS3 was identified in a large autism spectrum disorder cohort, published by O''Roak et al. in 2011. No further studies linking RBMS3 to neurodevelopmental disorders have appeared since the original publication (updated December 2025).

A frameshift variant in YWHAZ was identified in a mother with depression and her two sons with autism spectrum disorder (published by Toma et al. in 2014). No further studies linking YWHAZ to neurodevelopmental disorders have appeared since the original publication (updated December 2025).
comment: Es gibt hierzu eine Follow-up Studie: PMID: 32545830 in der folgender Satz steht: "Indeed, several exome sequencing studies in ASD patients found rare variants in YWHAZ and YWHAG [19,96,97]." Ich kann diese Varianten aber nicht finden.

synopsis: One individual with a de novo nonsense variant in FAM91A1 was identified in a large autism spectrum disorder cohort, published by Iossifov et al. in 2012. No further studies linking FAM91A1 to neurodevelopmental disorders have appeared since the original publication (updated December 2025).

One individual with a de novo nonsense variant in ATP1B1 was identified in a large autism spectrum disorder cohort, published by Iossifov et al. in 2012. No further studies linking ATP1B1 to neurodevelopmental disorders have appeared since the original publication (updated December 2025).

One individual with a de novo frameshift variant in DIP2A and one individual with a de novo nonsense variant were identified in large autism spectrum disorder cohorts, published by Iossifov et al. in 2012 and Iossifov et al. in 2014, respectively. Since then no further studies linking DIP2A to neurodevelopmental disorders have appeared since the original publication (updated May 2025).
